metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #239
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts

metadata.name: Vulvator #54
metadata.description:
A Collaboration of illustrator and artist Ma-Ka (Martta-Kaisa Virta) and artist Antti Pussinen.
The body-positive artwork explores the diversity and beauty of the vulva.
Instead of anatomic correctness, Ma-Ka tries to capture the the idea and aesthetic philosophy of the Origin of us all. 

There are at least 1632960 different illustration combinations + hash generated colors, backgrounds and textures.

All of them are rare and unique, so no trackable features.

Illustrations and concept by Ma-Ka, Code, colors and textures by Antti Pussinen.
All profits will be split 50/50 by the artists. 

More illustrations from Ma-Ka @
http://makaflux.com/
https://www.instagram.com/makavirta/

metadata.description:
Warning: GPU intensive!

Editions tiers:

(each tier will be unlocked upon the previous one's completion)

Realistic simulation of an emissive beam traversing a piece of glass of different color and density placed on a metallic surface

- Light bounces
- Frame Samples
- Screenshot Button (takes a screenshot...if it doesn't download, you should open the generator in a new tab)
- Rendering toggle (once you are satisfied with the output you can pause the rendering)

Created with threejs + three-gpu-pathtracer

metadata.name: Automaton III - Music Of The Spheres  #5
metadata.description:
"My intention is to let things be themselves" - John Cage

Sound is the main focal point of Automaton III, each sphere mapped to a note of a pentatonic scale. Each note sounds as the sphere makes impact with the ground, creating an indeterminate, never-repeating pattern of tones, which dissolve into the infinity of space.

Features:

- Star positioning is unique
- Star colour (Yellow, Purple, Green) 
- Line colour (Yellow, Purple, Green)
- Musical scale (arranged using a perlin noise function)
- Ball position and notes are random 

Click the button to enable/toggle sound.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #255
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Fantasized Telekinetic Obliteration #3
metadata.description:
An exploration on the ways in which mental energy might be captured and converted to kinetic destruction.

Each piece begins with an abstract shape. The shape is subjected to a field of disruptors, which contains a combination of beams and bombs. Beams slice through material, shearing fragments generally in the direction the beam is traveling. Bombs shatter material apart and eject shards away from the blast site.

All matter is conserved. That is, if the exploded and scattered fragments were reverted back to their initial positions, there would be a fully intact shape. No virtual particles. 🖤

Some structures may be annihilated. Others may take minor damage — or perhaps, none at all. Consult the “telekinetic power” feature for a full assessment.

---
- made with p5js
- press “s” to save png

metadata.name: SWTBD - construction drawing #83
metadata.description:
Construction drawing of the "Several ways to break down" generative geometry system by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut

mouse:

click: toggle active mode. In active mode, a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features is generated every 10s.

keyboard:

'a' or 'A' : add a slice or point
'e': decrease explosion factor
'E': increase explosion factor
'r' or 'R': create a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features
'+' and '-': zoom in and out
arrow keys: rotate around and translate along the vertical axis
